node.title: Sullivan: U.S. willing to talk to North Korea on nukes
node.description: President Biden's national security adviser said the U.S. is willing to negotiate "without preconditions" after North Korea launched another intercontinental ballistic missile.

node.title: Historian Yuval Noah Harari warns of dictatorship in Israel
node.description: The author says that in Israel, which has no constitution, the only check on governmental abuses of power is the Supreme Court, which is now under attack by forces that wish to rule with impunity.

node.title: Zoe Saldaña on "Special Ops: Lioness" – Action that's down-to-earth
node.description: She's the only actor to have starred in the top three highest-grossing movies – science fiction extravaganzas that transported audiences to other worlds. But at the moment Zoe Saldaña is focusing on more terrestrial roles, on-camera and off.

node.title: The history of the blockbuster movie
node.description: It's been assumed that the Hollywood summer blockbuster was born with the 1975 release of "Jaws," followed two years later by "Star Wars." But the film industry's desire for box office blockbusters existed long before a great white shark prowled the waters off Amity.

node.title: Kareem Abdul-Jabbar: "There are times when you don't have any choice but to speak the truth"
node.description: He was the all-time leading NBA scorer when he retired in 1989, after winning six world championships. But today Kareem Abdul-Jabbar prefers to focus on his role as an activist and social critic, writing with uncommon candor on Substack.

node.title: "Here Lies Love": A dance-pop musical on the life of Imelda Marcos
node.description: The story of the president and first lady of the Philippines, whose rule was ended by a "People Power" revolution in 1986, is now being told in an immersive Broadway musical set in a disco, created by David Byrne.

node.title: Christopher Nolan on J. Robert Oppenheimer, "the most important person who ever lived"
node.description: In his latest film, the director examines the efforts of the physicist and his race to build the atomic bomb that ended World War II. What happened after the war proved to be an entirely different power struggle, as Oppenheimer was accused of being a Russian agent.

node.title: Mediawatch: Could a 'mortgage bomb' blow up borrowers?
node.description: Recent reports have warned of a 'mortgage bomb' that could blow up - and a growing number of people unable to pay back debts. Is the story as explosive as some headlines would have you believe? Audio

node.title: Australia puts big tech under more pressure
node.description: Big tech companies have done deals with publishers to give them a return on sharing content from them. But the Australian government now also wants big fines for platforms publishing falsehoods. Audio

node.title: Evans and Cassidy post Formula E one-two in Rome
node.description: Jaguar's Mitch Evans won a crash-halted first of two Formula E races in Rome on Sunday, as fellow New Zealander Nick Cassidy retook the series lead.

node.title: Working mums get better deal at FIFA World Cup
node.description: Soccer-playing mums will be front-and-centre when the Women's World Cup kicks off this week after tenuous progress since the 2019 tournament for working mothers.

node.title: Carey not put off more stumpings in Ashes series
node.description: Australian wicketkeeper Alex Carey has said he won't hesitate to repeat his contentious stumping of England's Jonny Bairstow should a similar opportunity arise.

node.title: Gautrey narrowly misses podium at Olympic test regatta
node.description: New Zealand sailor George Gautrey is signing off from the Olympic test event without a medal but with plenty of invaluable experience following a week of competition in Marseille.

node.title: Cheika not getting carried away with Pumas upset win
node.description: Argentina coach Michael Cheika isn't getting carried away with the victory over the Wallabies and said he would have been happy even if the Pumas hadn't won.

node.title: Rice leaves West Ham for lucrative Arsenal deal
node.description: Arsenal have signed Declan Rice on a long-term contract from West Ham United, with manager Mikel Arteta describing the England star as an "exceptional talent".

node.title: Unseeded Vondrousova stuns Ons Jabeur to win Wimbledon title
node.description: Marketa Vondrousova plans to celebrate with beer and a new tattoo after becoming one of the most unlikely Wimbledon champions by beating Ons Jabeur in the final.

node.title: Aitchison sprints to world para athletics gold
node.description: New Zealand's Danielle Aitchison smashed the Oceania record to claim victory in the women's 200m T36 at the para athletics world championships.

node.title: Wilde blitzes the field for sprint distance World Triathlon Championship title in Hamburg
node.description: Olympic bronze medalist Hayden Wilde is the newly crowned Super Sprint World Triathlon Champion after winning the final in Hamburg with an early burst on the run.
